m five major cities, Invisible Nation looks backward at the historical context of family homelessness, as well as forward at what needs to be done to alleviate this widespread, although often hidden, poverty. Invisible Nation is a riveting must-read for anyone who wants to know what is happening to the millions of families living at the bottom of the economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aamerica.  aamerican history.  acities.  acrisis.  adomestic.  aeconomics.  aeconomy.  afamily issues.  ahealth.  ahomeless child.  ahomeless children.  ahomeless in america.  ahomeless population.  ahomeless problem.  ahomeless shelter.  ahomeless.  ahomelessness.  ahouseless.  ajournalism.  ajournalist.  apoverty.  apublic health.  asafety.  ashelters.  asocial issues.  asocial studies.  aunited states.  aurban.  awomens shelters.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052029267340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096609340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966093423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520966093/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY